Description

Can you get the flag? Download this binary.

The challenge provides a binary called gdbme and a set of GDB
instructions to follow. The goal is to get comfortable using GDB
as a debugger to extract a hidden flag.

----------------------------------------------------------------

Tools Used

- GDB (GNU Debugger)
- Kali Linux

----------------------------------------------------------------

Solution

Step 1 — Make the binary executable

    chmod +x gdbme

Step 2 — Open the binary in GDB

    gdb gdbme

Step 3 — Switch to assembly layout

    (gdb) layout asm

This opens a TUI view showing the disassembled instructions,
making it easier to follow the program's control flow.

Step 4 — Set a breakpoint

    (gdb) break *(main+99)

This sets a breakpoint at offset 99 inside main, pausing
execution right before a critical instruction.

Step 5 — Run the program

    (gdb) run

The program hits the breakpoint and pauses at main+99.

Step 6 — Jump over the check

    (gdb) jump *(main+104)

This jumps execution forward to main+104, skipping the
instructions between offsets 99 and 104.

----------------------------------------------------------------

What Actually Happened?

Between main+99 and main+104 sits a conditional jump — the
binary equivalent of an if statement. In normal execution, this
check would evaluate to false and redirect control flow away
from the flag-printing code.

By using jump, we manually redirected the instruction pointer
past that check, landing directly in the code path that prints
the flag — as if the condition had passed.

This is a classic technique in reverse engineering: instead of
figuring out what the correct input is, you bypass the check
entirely.

